                                        <h2>Employment And Training Services  </h2>

                                        <p>The Long Plain Employment and Training team consist of the Program Manager, Client Services Support Worker; Youth Coordinator; FNJF Coordinator and Receptionist. </p>

                                        <q>It takes team effort to provide excellent services to our band membership and thank them for their dedicated services throughout the year.</q>

                                        <p>The Long Plain Employment and Training Program (LPETP) provide services to the members of the First Nation. The LPETP is funded from the agreement between Service Canada and First Peoples Development Corporation. A five year agreement was renewed in 2010 and to expires in 2015 but has since been extended until 2017. LPETP is one of the thirty six sub-agreement holders in Southern Manitoba. First Peoples Development Corporation currently has five representatives from these sub-agreement holders who sit as Board members. This Board of Directors is the principle signers to the Master Agreement with Service Canada. </p>

                                        <div class="divider divider-center"><i class="icon-circle"></i>
                                        </div>
                                        <h2>Aboriginal Skills and Employment Training Strategies</h2>

                                        <p>Aboriginal Skills and Employment Training Strategies (ASETS) is the successor strategy to the former AHRDA. ASETS was designed improve the employment opportunities of Aboriginal peoples and enable them to fully participate in the Canadian economy. There are three programs under the Agreement that is signed every five years and consist of: Labour Market Consolidated Revenue Fund, Labour Market EI, Youth and Childcare. This new agreement has given us more flexibility in how we administer the program for employment programs such as urban, youth and disability and training as well as child care support services. Under the new 2010 ASETS agreement there are 3 key strategic priorities set out by Service Canada:</p>

                                        <ul>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>Support Demand Driven Skills Development </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>Foster partnership with private sector and across the whole-of- government (province and territories) </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>Emphasis on accountability for improved results. </p>
                                            </li>
                                        </ul>

                                        <p>The new ASETS funding is administered though the FDPI that is designed to help Aboriginal people prepare for and find high demand jobs quickly, as well as emphasis on retention. The following programs and services that are included under this funding are: </p>

                                        <ul>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>Skills development </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>Training for high demand jobs </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>Job finding </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>Youth employment and training </p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>Employment and training for urban and aboriginal peoples with disabilities</p>
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                <p>Access to childcare support</p>
                                            </li>
                                        </ul>

